I am quoting from The Complete Book of Furniture Repair and Refinishing -
Ralph Parsons Kinney
&quot;Thin shellac with alcohol to the consistency of water and apply with an old
nylon stocking made into a ball, squeezing out a little of the material at a
time.

Dip the pad in the shellac solution and apply with straight strokes. As
soon as it's dry, continue to apply more coats until a sheen or gloss is
acquired. If cracks appear on the surface, sprinkle on a little pumice
stone and rub. Then apply more coats of the shellac until the cracks are
filled.

Allow time for the surface to dry completely. Then put onlly a few drops of
raw linseed oil on the pad, and rub with a circular motion over the entire
area, adding a few more drops of the oil as needed. When a high polish is
seen, add no more oil,. but coninue rubbing until the surface is thoroughly
dry. Allow to stand overnight, and repeat the rubbing with the oil.&quot;

Hope this is what you wanted.
Terry Leon
