I saw on television just last night how important a finish can be. On one
of those shows where they have appraisers access items brought in by people.
There was a couple who had an old cherry highboy that her brother had given
them 50 years ago. As they didn't like the dark, nearly black finish on the
cherry wood, they had it refinished. Apparently, this piece was from the
18th century. They appeared very upset when the appraiser told them it made
a difference between the piece being worth $30,000 instead of nearly
$250,000 because the collectors of this style of furniture preferred the
original dark finish. While I don't think I'll ever see a piece worth that
much, it almost scares me away from refinishing.

